        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>ALMA is the ideal instrument to carry out this project. It represents a massive improvement over previous LiH observations. Friedel, Kemball, &amp; Fields (2011) have set the best constraints to date on the abundance of Li toward any source (~80 mJy/beam). However, these ALMA observations will improve on their observed S/N by a factor of at least 15, allowing us to definitively answer questions about the existence of LiH and by extension LiH in the ISM. We are asking for a sensitivity of 5 mJy in order to not only detect the strongest part of the LiH line, but also to be able to study the line's profile and compare it to other known species toward this source (CO, HCN, HCO+). This noise level will also allow us to study the full line profile of the molecular transitions of CO, HCN, and HCO+ to an unprecedented sensitivity.  We have selected a channel width of ~0.28 km/s. Based on previous, lower J, observations of CO, HCN, and HCO+ toward this source by Combes &amp; Wiklind (1995) and Wiklind &amp; Combes (1995) this resolution will give us at least 100 channels across these spectral lines. This is an order of magnitude better than the spectral resolution of previous observations and will allow us to study the line profiles in exceptional detail and compare the line profiles to their lower J counterparts. While the line width of the LiH line appears to be narrower than that of the other species (~3.2 km/s, Combes &amp; Wiklind (1998)), we will still have at least 10 channels across the line. We note that this does increase the data rate modestly to 21.7 MB/s but argue that this is needed; a lower frequency resolution would not meet the science goals of this proposal.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
